  "target_response": {
    "text": "HRV stands for heart rate variability: the small changes in timing from one heartbeat to the next. When you're rested and relaxed the gaps vary more; when you're run down, stressed, or fighting something off, the rhythm gets more metronome-like. Trackers use it as a rough gauge of how ready your body is for effort. Since you log by hand, I don't have an HRV reading for you, and honestly you don't need one to train well. Your own signals do a similar job: morning energy, how quickly you recover between sessions, and sleep, like the 7.3 hours you logged last night. If you're curious someday, a device can add detail, but a simple morning energy note in your log gives us most of the same coaching value.",
